Since `polar _ _` is a set, we usually use a theorem claiming `Set.Nonempty`, not an instance claiming `_root_.Nonempty`. Do you need the instance for some reason?

@urkud currently I'm using it here: https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/16316/files#diff-b605c62b370366aa8783f5424b695ad108ee3f82e0f878dc48c9c3ade63cd8c2R343

Maybe there's another way to do that though?
I've fixed #16316 using `haveI` (for now at least). I've made the instances in this PR theorems instead.
Why not reuse `LinearMap.zero_mem_polar` in the proof? I think that `LinearMap.zero_mem_polar _ s` will work as a proof.

You can use
```suggestion
theorem polar_nonempty (s : Set E) : Set.Nonempty (B.polar s) := by
  use 0
  exact zero_mem_polar B s

instance polar.instNonempty (s : Set E) : Nonempty (B.polar s) :=
  (polar_nonempty s).to_subtype
```
if you need an instance (same below). Note that the theorem uses `Set.Nonempty`, not `_root_.Nonempty`.
Thanks!
bors d+
Thanks, I've changed both the `polar_nonempty` results to use `Set.Nonempty`. I'll keep the instances out of this PR and add them to #16316 instead so they can be considered there.
